## 🔑 How Integration Works

### 1. **Shell App Responsibilities**
- **Routing:** The shell app manages routes and delegates them to the correct micro‑frontend using reverse proxy logic (e.g., `/dashboard` → React container, `/users` → Angular container).  [DEV Community](https://dev.to/alberto_martinez/building-a-modular-architecture-with-microservices-microfrontends-and-a-local-shell-app-3m13)  
- **Authentication:** It centralizes JWT token validation and issues tokens to frontends for secure sessions.  [DEV Community](https://dev.to/alberto_martinez/building-a-modular-architecture-with-microservices-microfrontends-and-a-local-shell-app-3m13)  
- **Dynamic Loading:** Micro‑frontends are loaded at runtime via **dynamic JS imports** or **Webpack Module Federation**, ensuring independent deployment and scaling.  [DEV Community](https://dev.to/alberto_martinez/building-a-modular-architecture-with-microservices-microfrontends-and-a-local-shell-app-3m13)  

---

### 2. **Integration Strategies**
| Strategy | How It Works | Pros | Cons |
|----------|--------------|------|------|
| **Web Components** | Each micro‑frontend is compiled into a custom element (`<angular-microfrontend>`). The shell app simply includes it via `<script>` and uses the tag.  [LinkedIn](https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/microfrontend-integration-strategies-web-components-es-yash-garg-6xb5c)  [omid.dev](https://omid.dev/2024/05/11/micro-frontends-working-example/) | Framework‑agnostic, encapsulated styling, reusable | Verbose setup, polyfills needed for older browsers |
| **Self‑contained ES Modules** | Each micro‑frontend is bundled into a standalone file exporting a render function. The shell app calls the function to mount it.  [LinkedIn](https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/microfrontend-integration-strategies-web-components-es-yash-garg-6xb5c) | Independent deployment, simple runtime | Larger bundle sizes, duplication of dependencies |
| **Module Federation (Webpack 5)** | Micro‑frontends expose components at build time. The shell dynamically imports them at runtime.  [DEV Community](https://dev.to/alberto_martinez/building-a-modular-architecture-with-microservices-microfrontends-and-a-local-shell-app-3m13)  [LinkedIn](https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/microfrontend-integration-strategies-web-components-es-yash-garg-6xb5c) | Shared dependencies, efficient loading | Requires consistent build tooling |

---

### 3. **Communication Between Shell & Micro‑frontends**
- **Shared State:** The shell owns global state and passes data via attributes or props.  [omid.dev](https://omid.dev/2024/05/11/micro-frontends-working-example/)  
- **Event Contracts:** Micro‑frontends dispatch DOM events (e.g., `microfrontend:message`) to communicate back to the shell.  [omid.dev](https://omid.dev/2024/05/11/micro-frontends-working-example/)  
- **Registry Database:** A local DB tracks active modules, ports, and routes, enabling dynamic route mapping and error handling.  [DEV Community](https://dev.to/alberto_martinez/building-a-modular-architecture-with-microservices-microfrontends-and-a-local-shell-app-3m13)  

